Turkey is broadening its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands on horseback between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world as some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the size of the enterprise of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British forces and dominatrixes advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 an ammunition train broke out destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has been slowly crumbling, largely outdated by history.
But today, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all points to the east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's growing diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has created an entire new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new commitment policy.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bouncing race along the tracks that produced the old-world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by shopping malls built means and bakeries of power, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
“The purpose of the foreign policy party is now to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today he must look east and west at the same time.
It was not the case of one or the other.
They must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
“Turkey,” he says, “doesn’t want to face that choice.”
Then he points out one point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has recited by heart: the ties of the Middle East not only to the Middle East, but also to the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can metaphorically travel those rail lines eastward across Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe's Middle East ambitions can now largely be in Turkey's hands.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back across the Bosporus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At least then there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent to advance demands on this fascinating country.
