The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, this time Nissan was inspired by nature, and bees in particular.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking for example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, or the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is an expansion of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer’s vehicles.
During the flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of bees, able to see in all directions with an angle of more than 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, the engineers developed what they called a laser range finder.
This mechanism detects obstacles facing the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance from the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately prevents collision.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right or greater angles to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
“If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect upwards or downwards, or even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which it can turn its wheels and not exploiting infinite directions and ways like bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
“This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple of dozens of KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, and we’re not talking about mega.”
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on the route.
