Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
To establish the republic on a socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
According to the official results, 64% of voters voted “yes” to the referendum, on a basis of 80%.
According to these results, the "no" was 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% white cards.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it would have to get half the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polls and an estimate from a non-governmental organization announced a crushing victory of the “yes”, placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously", he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians in the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The ballot, which took place in full calm according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the “development planning” of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction implemented by large foreign companies and consequently their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to take advantage of this amendment and to propose its candidacy for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions who were kidnapped 10 days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held in the desert for ten days were safely returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently fit, the hostages arrived at the military base in Almaza, near Cairo International Airport, around 15:30 a.m., aboard a special aircraft.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any press interviews, to the Maadi hospital, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They are in “good health” and no ransom has been paid “to the kidnappers,” Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
Kidnapped on Sept. 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been whipped from one hideout to the next by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptus, the safari agency.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight, shortly before dawn.
"There were shotshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," the official said.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the “blitz” unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We have to admit that if we achieved that result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, the special forces," he said, without adding any further details.
He also denied payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army said it had intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which were the kidnappers and killed six, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and captured two.
According to the army, the kidnappers are linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
On the front page a debate on the financing of culture focuses on the current election campaign.
So much the better.
But a part of our cultural life is always in the shadows.
Who will speak out to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or hunger-stricken national historic places?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying three and a half million euros for the restoration of the Château de Chinon, in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that affirms that the protection of heritage is part of the national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, every political authority and every government department, and all this by common accord.
In Quebec, at the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, there are at least 40,000 volunteers who, grouped into 211 societies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and heritage assets preserve, with little money, private archives and archaeological sites.
They are the very ones who often defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision makers attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help through partial nationalization the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which ended up in difficulty for the first time in Europe due to the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands on the weekend agreed at the highest level, also involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the difficulties in which the international financial market has been struggling for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard may constitute a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank’s share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first of all the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis’ actions had begun with a vertical collapse, and serious signs of the institution’s crisis appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank’s shares fell nearly 12 percent on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has declined by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current share prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank’s executives this value is not real.
The company’s summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the $700 billion US plan.
On Monday, the title slowly resumed.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new managing director of the bank.
The financial institution has also been looking for private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a deserving offer.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they should not be afraid to lose money.
There was no panic among the bank’s customers, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns autonomous subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
Insurers on life and health, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like handing over the chicken coop to the fox,” writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick, author of the program to follow prescriptions.
Insurance companies subordinate the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims to the health of the customer and if they consider the risk too high they do not stipulate the insurance.
A long time ago the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the outcome of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies about what medicines he bought in the last year and a half and from this the program evinces what diseases he suffers from and what health condition he is in.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers this means that your blood fat level is virtually incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so in addition to paper work there is not much left, even if small difficulties arise.
Among the cons are that some medicines are usable for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, applies as an increased risk factor, the first two do not.
For the request and processing of data, separate companies have been formed and these, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities force them to do so even if they have not so far imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies recently also process the results of laboratory tests and link them to the data of medicine consumption in order to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to the data and at the same time the control of the use will be more and more difficult.
There is a separate privacy law, but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives supervisory authority to companies specializing in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: that is why he has developed a program that links the forwarding of data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
Global Marseilles menu
EU and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are partners that trade mainly with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting has also been dominated by this theme, in addition to all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit that will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is becoming a major democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member states have yet to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So there was no emphasis on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, in his capacity as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso Chairman of the Committee and Javier Solana High Representative for Foreign Affairs received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double in 5 years, that is to increase to 100 billion euros, trade.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not too ambitious a goal.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The goal is to balance because while the EU is India’s first trading partner, New Delhi is only in ninth place among the EU’s partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms on both sides, and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed its persistence in the energy and climate agenda, which would reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the fact that we should sign a global pact at the climate conference scheduled for next year and reduce greenhouse gas production by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb rising food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital today, where he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, it is hoped that to build Indian nuclear reactors, French companies will receive a commission worth 20 billion euros.
According to information from our news agency the agreement would last 15 years.
