Steve Fossett's plane was found, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fossett's plane was found, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at 3000 meters above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
Wooden County Sheriff John Anderson said: “The plane has been located, we’ve sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it’s exactly what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared.”
The sheriff said no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was put to death in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (Ntsb) said hours after the wreck was sighted a team of investigators had been dispatched, who then identified the device: the Bellanca 8kcab, which had been missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some personal belongings of Fossett had been found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search had been halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete the world tour on an air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he had travelled around the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among his many records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, above the Andes, but with a copilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
An out-of-the-box SUV with an original design and well defined by firm lines, wide surfaces and sharp angles.
This, in short, is the latest Glk to be born among the "compact" offroads of the starhouse with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a breath of innovation in this sector.
Due to its content outside the traditional canons, the communication that will accompany the launch of the SUV Glk, available at the Mercedes-Benz showrooms from 17 October, will also be unexpected and unconventional.
Thus the hype that will accompany the debut of the new car will initiate an unprecedented mode of communication also through a futuristic campaign of 3D posters, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A maxi-poster project, divided into three different phases, that will dominate the central shopping street of Milan, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision and thanks to special glasses distributed near Corso Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in near real size and in three-dimensional format.
In fact, looking at the image you will have the impression that the car is out of the poster.
Subsequently, through the use of innovative Elumina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated at different times in all its details, then recomposed into a single image.
Undoubtedly Mercedes with this advertisement is trying to introduce something new in the stereotypical field of automotive communication.
Will it succeed with this formula to arouse the interest of future buyers? We will see.
